            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Sean Miller\u2019s love for art was born not in a bohemian enclave, but in a quiet Chicago suburb, nurtured by his librarian mother's weekend trips to the city's grand museums. While his engineer father preached practicality, Sean saw story and emotion in the careful arrangement of objects behind glass. This passion led him to an MFA in Museum Studies from the University of Illinois, his head filled with dreams of curating exhibits on ancient civilizations.\n\nThe reality of the academic world was a harsh awakening: a landscape of unpaid internships and brutal competition for a handful of poorly paid positions. To make ends meet, he took a \"temporary\" job designing window displays for Marshall Field's. This pragmatic choice became a career-defining revelation. He discovered he could tell compelling stories, evoke moods, and engage a far broader audience with mannequins and merchandise than with dusty artifacts. He wasn't selling out; he was taking the museum to the street.\n\nHis talent for turning retail space into an immersive experience propelled him up the corporate ladder, from Chicago to New York, and finally, fifteen years ago, to San Francisco for a director-level position. Today, Sean is a respected figure in the industry, orchestrating the visual identity of a major apparel brand.\n\nHe lives in a meticulously curated Cole Valley apartment, a personal museum of mid-century furniture, local art, and books on design theory. His daily 4.8-mile commute on the N Judah streetcar is a cherished ritual\u2014a time for observation and quiet contemplation before the bustle of his downtown office. Evenings are often spent trying new restaurants in Hayes Valley or hosting small dinner parties. A long-term relationship ended amicably a few years back, and while he\u2019s open to a new connection, his life is full with a close-knit circle of friends in creative fields.\n\nSean\u2019s ultimate dream is to bring his journey full circle. He aspires to one day leave the corporate world and open his own small, thoughtfully designed home goods store in his neighborhood, a final project where he is the sole curator of a space built for beauty, function, and community."
