        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "Here are 5 significant memories for Sean Miller:\n\n1.\nHe remembers being nine, his hand lost in his mother\u2019s, standing before the Thorne Miniature Rooms at the Art Institute. Others saw dollhouses; he saw entire lives contained in silent, perfect detail. That day, staring into those tiny, curated worlds, he understood that arranging objects was a language\u2014his language. The quiet revelation planted a seed that his father\u2019s practicality could never uproot, proving that emotion could be engineered through design. It became the foundation of his worldview.\n\n2.\nIt was 2 AM, the week before Christmas, his first year at Marshall Field\u2019s. Exhausted, he stepped onto a frigid State Street to see his finished holiday window. Through the glass, the scene he'd built\u2014mannequins in velvet, faux snow, artfully placed gifts\u2014glowed. A lone taxi slowed, the driver just gazing for a moment. He felt a jolt of connection more potent than any academic praise. He wasn't just selling coats; he was giving the city a moment of wonder. He was a curator for the public.\n\n3.\nHis first week in San Francisco, fifteen years ago, he boarded the N Judah at sunrise. As the streetcar rumbled out of the Sunset Tunnel, the city unfurled below\u2014a collage of fog, rooftops, and early morning light. It felt less like a commute and more like a cinematic reveal. Looking at the diverse faces reflected in the window, he felt an overwhelming sense of rightness, a quiet click of a piece locking into place. This city, and this ride, would be his. It was the moment he truly arrived.\n\n4.\nA few years back, the week after his partner moved out, the silence in his apartment felt cavernous. Instead of despairing, he spent a Saturday rearranging his living room, moving the Eames chair to catch the afternoon light just so. As he placed a favorite ceramic bowl on a now-empty shelf, he didn't feel loss, but a quiet reclamation of space. He realized his home wasn't half-empty; it was wholly his again. It taught him the profound comfort of being the sole curator of his own peace.\n\n5.\nAbout a year ago, walking home through Cole Valley after dinner with friends, he paused before a darkened, empty storefront. He\u2019d passed it a hundred times, but tonight, he saw it all: the warm lighting, the clean lines of shelving, a single perfect vase in the window. The abstract dream of his own shop suddenly had a physical address. It wasn't an escape from his career, but the ultimate expression of it\u2014a final, personal exhibit. In that moment, the future felt less like a question and more like a blueprint."
